\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.11}{\ignorespaces Geodesics-in-heat approximation of the distance to a dense red non-convex source curve on a two-dimensional grid. The first panel shows the exact Euclidean distance to the curve. The other panels diffuse a narrow band around the same curve by one backward-Euler resolvent step with Neumann boundary conditions, then recover an approximate distance by the normalized-gradient Poisson solve. Each panel is robustly normalized, and the contour values are chosen from quantiles of the displayed field so that level lines are distributed evenly across the image. Increasing the resolvent scale $\tau $ stabilizes the sparse linear solves but progressively rounds the non-convex geometry of the level sets.}}{114}{figure.7.11}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:sinkhorn-geodesics-in-heat}{{7.11}{114}{Geodesics-in-heat approximation of the distance to a dense red non-convex source curve on a two-dimensional grid. The first panel shows the exact Euclidean distance to the curve. The other panels diffuse a narrow band around the same curve by one backward-Euler resolvent step with Neumann boundary conditions, then recover an approximate distance by the normalized-gradient Poisson solve. Each panel is robustly normalized, and the contour values are chosen from quantiles of the displayed field so that level lines are distributed evenly across the image. Increasing the resolvent scale $\tau $ stabilizes the sparse linear solves but progressively rounds the non-convex geometry of the level sets}{figure.7.11}{}}
