\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {13.9}{\ignorespaces Balanced and unbalanced gradient flows of $\KL  (\rho |\beta )$ for one-dimensional Gaussian mixtures. In each panel the colored density stacks correspond to five increasing times, from red to blue, and the faint gray curve repeated on each row is the target mixture $\beta $. The balanced Wasserstein flow is the conservative Fokker--Planck equation, so mass must move through the low-density region between modes. The $\WFR  _\kappa $ flow adds the birth--death reaction term in\nobreakspace  {}\textup  {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont  (\ignorespaces \ref  {eq-wfr-kl-flow}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}; it attenuates overrepresented regions and creates missing mass near target modes, reaching the target shape much faster.}}{221}{figure.13.9}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:gradflow-wfr-unbalanced-flow}{{13.9}{221}{Balanced and unbalanced gradient flows of $\KL (\rho |\beta )$ for one-dimensional Gaussian mixtures. In each panel the colored density stacks correspond to five increasing times, from red to blue, and the faint gray curve repeated on each row is the target mixture $\beta $. The balanced Wasserstein flow is the conservative Fokker--Planck equation, so mass must move through the low-density region between modes. The $\WFR _\kappa $ flow adds the birth--death reaction term in~\eqref {eq-wfr-kl-flow}; it attenuates overrepresented regions and creates missing mass near target modes, reaching the target shape much faster}{figure.13.9}{}}
