\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {13.11}{\ignorespaces Brunn--Minkowski through an affine optimal-transport interpolation between two ellipses. For ellipses, the Brenier map is affine, so the transported support $T_t(A)$ remains an ellipse and its area is computed exactly from the determinant of $(1-t)\mathrm  {Id}+tDT$. The right panel shows that $|T_t(A)|^{1/2}$ lies above the linear interpolation of the endpoint square-root areas, which is the two-dimensional determinant concavity behind the proof of Brunn--Minkowski.}}{228}{figure.13.11}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:gradflow-brunn-minkowski-ot}{{13.11}{228}{Brunn--Minkowski through an affine optimal-transport interpolation between two ellipses. For ellipses, the Brenier map is affine, so the transported support $T_t(A)$ remains an ellipse and its area is computed exactly from the determinant of $(1-t)\Id +tDT$. The right panel shows that $|T_t(A)|^{1/2}$ lies above the linear interpolation of the endpoint square-root areas, which is the two-dimensional determinant concavity behind the proof of Brunn--Minkowski}{figure.13.11}{}}
